<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="55" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="55">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. rufescens" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="rufescens">L. rufescens</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Sicariidae" genus="Loxosceles" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Loxosceles foutadjalloni" order="Araneae" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foutadjalloni">Loxosceles foutadjalloni</taxonomicName>
Millot, 1941; in having male palpal tibia wide and a long embolus (
<bibRefCitation author="Lotz, LN" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" pagination="1 - 41" title="Present status of Sicariidae (Arachnida: Araneae) in the Afrotropical region." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/Zootaxa.4341.4.2" volume="3522" year="2012">Lotz 2012</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 9C), however in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. rufescens" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="rufescens">L. rufescens</taxonomicName>
the male palp tibia is wider and the embolus is sigmoid-shaped (Figs 68-69), whereas in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. foutadjalloni" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="foutadjalloni">L. foutadjalloni</taxonomicName>
the embolus is long and curved (
<bibRefCitation author="Lotz, LN" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" pagination="1 - 41" title="Present status of Sicariidae (Arachnida: Araneae) in the Afrotropical region." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/Zootaxa.4341.4.2" volume="3522" year="2012">Lotz 2012</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 9C). Females resemble 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. foutadjalloni" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="foutadjalloni">L. foutadjalloni</taxonomicName>
by the shape of the seminal receptacles (
<bibRefCitation author="Lotz, LN" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" pagination="1 - 41" title="Present status of Sicariidae (Arachnida: Araneae) in the Afrotropical region." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/Zootaxa.4341.4.2" volume="3522" year="2012">Lotz 2012</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 10B), however in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. rufescens" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="rufescens">L. rufescens</taxonomicName>
they are short and round distally (Fig. 70), whereas in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. foutadjalloni" pageId="16" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="foutadjalloni">L. foutadjalloni</taxonomicName>
the seminal receptacles are longer and distally bifurcated and rounded (
<bibRefCitation author="Lotz, LN" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" pagination="1 - 41" title="Present status of Sicariidae (Arachnida: Araneae) in the Afrotropical region." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/Zootaxa.4341.4.2" volume="3522" year="2012">Lotz 2012</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 10B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="55" type="description">
